The fluorescence response of gel PQPA to metal ions such as Fe3+, Ca2+, Hg2+, Mg2+, Ag+, Cu2+, Cd2+, Co2+, Zn2+, Al3+, Ni2+, Cr3+ and Pb2+ (water solution, c = 0.1 M) were carefully researched. Before adding metal ions, the gel PQPA has a strong emission peak at 470 nm. When abovementioned metal ions were added to the gel PQPA respectively, only Fe3+ have response and other metal ions have no effect (Figs. 3a, c and S4). It was clear that gel PQPA could detect Fe3+ with specific selectivity. Furthermore, the association constant (Ka) for the complexation between gel PQPA and Fe3+ was estimated by means of fluorescence titrations (Fig. 4
                           ). According to the relevant formula (Fig. S6), the Ka was obtained as 5.80 × 109 M−1, the gel PQPA and Fe3+ were formed a 1:1 complex. The LOD for Fe3+ was estimated to be 0.102 nM based on 3δ/S method (Fig. S8) [40]. It is worth mentioning that the gel PQPA has ultrasensitive response property for Fe3+ compared to previously reported sensors (Table 1
                           ) [47–53].

Because the gel PQPA shows ultrasensitive response for Fe3+, so, a novel no fluorescence metallogel PQPA-Fe was constructed by adding Fe3+ into the gel PQPA. Then, in the same way, the fluorescence response of metallogel PQPA-Fe to anions such as F−, AcO−, ClO4
                           −, CN−, Cl−, SCN−, HSO4
                           −, H2PO4
                           −, Br− and I− (water solution, c = 0.1 M) were investigated. When the F− was added into the metallogel PQPA-Fe, the gel shows fluorescent “turn-on” response for F−. Other anions could not induce any significant changes in the fluorescence spectrum of the metallogel PQPA-Fe (Figs. 3b, d and S5). Clearly, the metallogel PQPA-Fe could selectively sense F−. Furthermore, the association constant (Ka) for the complexation between metallogel PQPA-Fe and F− was estimated by means of fluorescence titrations (Fig. 5
                           ). According to the relevant formula (Fig. S7), the Ka was obtained as 8.89 × 106 M−2, the metallogel PQPA-Fe and F− were formed a 1:2 complex. The LOD for F− was estimated to be 9.79 nM based on 3δ/S method (Fig. S9) [40]. Fortunately, metallogel PQPA-Fe has a lower detection line than some of the reported F− fluorescence sensors (Table 2
                           ) [11–13,54–57].

IR, XRD and SEM spectra also provide further evidence for the assembly process of the host-guest. In the IR spectra (Fig. 7
                        ), the band at 1665 cm−1 was attributed to the vibration absorption peaks of CN from 8-hydroxyquinoline group of P5Q powder. However, the vibration absorption peaks of CN of xerogel PQPA shifted from 1665 cm−1 to 1693 cm−1. The XRD spectra of P5Q powder and xerogel PQPA are shown in Fig. 8
                        . For the P5Q powder didn't show peaks, nonetheless, the xerogel PQPA showed four peaks at 2θ = 23.64°, 23.93°, 24.61° and 25.50°. The corresponding d-spacings are 3.76, 3.71, 3.62 and 3.49 Å, respectively. Under the SEM, P5Q exists in amorphous powder (Fig. S15a), nevertheless, xerogel PQPA showed lamellar stacking structure (Fig. S15b). The above experimental results also verify the successful construction of SOF gel PQPA.
